lobbying_activities: [{'general_issue_code': 'AGR', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Agriculture', 'description': 'H.R.2 - Agriculture Improvement Act of 2018, made recommended improvements such as addressing the legal gray area of whether delta-8 and other hemp-derived intoxicants are defined as "industrial hemp". Provisions of the 2018 Act explicitly legalize the possession of cannabinoids that are naturally occurring constituents of hemp, but it does not impact the control status of synthetically derived cannabinoids. This created a proliferation of THC hemp-derived products in states where cannabis is legal or not, creating a parallel market. We advocated for more safety measures to be put into place and for Congress to clarify the definition of what constitutes as industrial hemp.', 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 125126, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'TOI', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'HUTCHINSON', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': None, 'new': False}], 'government_entities': []}, {'general_issue_code': 'BAN', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Banking', 'description': 'H.R.1996 - SAFE Banking Act: This bill generally prohibits a federal banking regulator from penalizing a depository institution for providing banking services to a legitimate cannabis-related business (Safe Harbor for Banks). Prohibited penalties include terminating or limiting the deposit insurance or share insurance of a depository institution solely because the institution provides financial services to a legitimate cannabis-related business and prohibiting or otherwise discouraging a depository institution from offering financial services to such a business. This removes a major barrier of entry for small cannabis businesses and protects them from potential theft as most cannabis businesses operate under cash-only.', 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 125126, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'TOI', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'HUTCHINSON', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': None, 'new': False}], 'government_entities': []}]

lobbying_activities: [{'general_issue_code': 'FIR', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Firearms/Guns/Ammunition', 'description': 'The National Association for Gun Rights advocates on behalf of gun owners for pro-Second Amendment related public policy issues including but not limited to the following subject areas and their respective executive departments/agencies and legislative committees: Firearms, ammunition, accessories, right to possess purchase own and carry, background checks, mental health, NICS, registration requirements/databases, federal gun free zones, NFA of 1934, GCA of 1968, gun related Executive Orders, actions, nominations or treaties, 1st and 4th amendment protections for gun owners, and related appropriations. In each case NAGR opposes gun control and supports removing restrictions on the right to bear arms. Legislation before the 117th Congress that NAGR is actively following and lobbying on may include, but is not limited to: House Bills and Resolutions: H.R. 28, H.R. 38, H.R. 48, H.R. 52, H.R. 53, H.R. 100, H.R. 151, H.R. 152, H.R. 168, H.R. 173, H.R. 283, H.R. 363, H.R. 374, H.R. 381, H.R. 396, H.R. 450, H.R. 646, H.R. 660, H.R. 698, H.R. 715, H.R. 730, H.R. 768, H.R. 790, H.R. 816, H.R. 1095, H.R. 1271, H.R. 1699, H.R. 2392, H.R. 2418, H.R. 2502, H.R. 2538,. H.J. Res. 44, H.R. 2753, H.R. 2985, H.R. 3018, H.R. 3122, H.R. 3155, H.R. 3212, H.R. 4201,. H.R. 4283 Senate Bills and Resolutions: S. 14, S. 25, S. 163, S. 173, S. 203, S. 252, S. 361, S. 401, S. 827, S. 951, S. 1383, S. 1949. Kay Bailey Hutchison', 'new': False}], 'government_entities': [{'id': 2, 'name': 'HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES'}]}, {'general_issue_code': 'MMM', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Medicare/Medicaid', 'description': 'Support HR 2665, the Supporting Safety Net Hospitals Act, which would repeal cuts to the Medicaid Disproportionate Share Hospital Program. Support for congressional House sign-on letter to leadership asking them to address the cuts to the Medicaid Disproportionate Share Hospital Program. Support for The Save Rural Hospitals Act (S. 803), which would establish a national minimum rate of 0.85 for the Area Wage Index reimbursement rate. Support for Rural Hospital Support Act (S. 1110), which would make the low-volume Medicare adjustment (LVA) and Medicare-dependent Hospital (MDH) program permanent, as well as add an additional base year MDHs could choose when calculating their payments. Request congressional engagement on Informational Bulletin released by CMS on February 17, 2023 related to permissible state financing arrangements in the Medicaid program. Oppose H.R. 3281, the Transparent PRICE Act, which would require additional reporting by hospitals on pricing. Oppose H.R. 3290, which requires additional reporting by hospitals participating in the 340B program. Oppose H.R. 3262, which requires new reporting by hospitals about ownership structure. Oppose H.R. 3237, which implements a site-neutral payment policy for drugs administered at off-campus hospital outpatient departments. Oppose site-neutral payment policies (generally) that reduce payments to hospitals for services delivered at off-campus hospital outpatient departments. Provide comments to CMS on CMS-2445-P Medicaid Program; Disproportionate Share Hospital Third-Party Payer Rule; provisions related to Hospital-Specific DSH Payment Limit ( 447.295) and Limitations on Aggregate Payments for DSHs Beginning October 1, 1992 ( 447.297). Provide comments to CMS on CMS-1788-P Medicare Program; Medicare Disproportionate Share Hospital (DSH) Payments: Counting Certain Days Associated With Section 1115 Demonstrations in the Medicaid Fraction; opposing a proposal to eliminate section 1115 demonstration waiver inpatient days that are associated with uncompensated care pools. Provide comments to CMS on CMS-1785-P CMS-1785-P, Medicare Program; Hospital Inpatient Prospective Payment Systems for Acute Care Hospitals and the Long-Term Care Hospital Prospective Payment System and Policy Changes and Fiscal Year 2024 Rates; Quality Programs and Medicare Promoting Interoperability Program Requirements for Eligible Hospitals and Critical Access Hospitals; Rural Emergency Hospital and Physician-Owned Hospital Requirements; and Disclosure of Ownership; provisions related to IPPS payments to hospitals, funding for medical residents at Rural Emergency Hospitals, and others. lobbying_activities: [{'general_issue_code': 'AGR', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Agriculture', 'description': 'H.R.2 - Agriculture Improvement Act of 2018, made recommended improvements such as addressing the legal gray area of whether delta-8 and other hemp-derived intoxicants are defined as "industrial hemp". Provisions of the 2018 Act explicitly legalize the possession of cannabinoids that are naturally occurring constituents of hemp, but it does not impact the control status of synthetically derived cannabinoids. This created a proliferation of THC hemp-derived products in states where cannabis is legal or not, creating a parallel market. We advocated for more safety measures to be put into place and for Congress to clarify the definition of what constitutes as industrial hemp.', 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 125126, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'TOI', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'HUTCHINSON', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': None, 'new': False}], 'government_entities': [{'id': 2, 'name': 'HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES'}]}, {'general_issue_code': 'BAN', 'general_issue_code_display': 'Banking', 'description': 'H.R.1996 - SAFE Banking Act: This bill generally prohibits a federal banking regulator from penalizing a depository institution for providing banking services to a legitimate cannabis-related business (Safe Harbor for Banks). Prohibited penalties include terminating or limiting the deposit insurance or share insurance of a depository institution solely because the institution provides financial services to a legitimate cannabis-related business and prohibiting or otherwise discouraging a depository institution from offering financial services to such a business. This removes a major barrier of entry for small cannabis businesses and protects them from potential theft as most cannabis businesses operate under cash-only.', 'foreign_entity_issues': '', 'lobbyists': [{'lobbyist': {'id': 125126, 'prefix': None, 'prefix_display': None, 'first_name': 'TOI', 'nickname': None, 'middle_name': None, 'last_name': 'HUTCHINSON', 'suffix': None, 'suffix_display': None}, 'covered_position': None, 'new': False}], 'government_entities': [{'id': 2, 'name': 'HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES'}]}]
